		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>London</placeName> <date>Novr. 21St 1854</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">My dear friend.</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">Once again am I on the<lb/> move&#44; about to cross the wide <placeName>Atlantic</placeName>&#44; and return to my old feeding<lb/> ground&#44; <placeName>Kingston&#44; Jamaica</placeName>.  The departure of <persName>Mr. D. E. Sauson<add>&#63;</add></persName>&#44; <persName>Mrs.<lb/> Nathan&#39;s</persName> only brother&#44; for the &#8220;land of life&#8221; on the <date>21st</date> Ulto<add>&#63;</add> occasions<lb/> this more&#44; nay&#44; makes it obligatory&#59; for not only are my interests at<lb/> stake&#44; but a young widow and three helpless babies and&#44; by will&#44; solemnly<lb/> committed to my future care.  It is a very onerous charge&#44; but  the work<lb/> must be done&#59; may the Omnipotent grant me strength to perform it faithfully.<lb/> My brother in law was but 31 years of age&#44; his disease scarlet fever&#44; and<lb/> after 4 days illness his spirit fled.  <persName>Mrs. Nathan</persName> for several weeks prior<lb/> to the receipt of the intelligence had been alarmingly ill&#59; and you can<lb/> conceive the shock the news imparted to her enfeebled frame.  Had this<lb/> melancholy event not occurred&#44; its summer had probably seen us again in<lb/> <placeName>America</placeName>&#44; its country&#44; par excellence&#44; in my and <persName>Mrs. N&#39;s</persName> ideas.  But it was<lb/> not to be.  <placeName>Jamaica</placeName> will be henceforth my abode&#44; not from choice&#44; but<lb/> circumstances.  My heart is too full&#44; and my brain too busy to write you<lb/> more.  I have not recd. Your Bible&#44; nor my <persName>Job</persName>.  When the latter is<lb/> returned to you send it on to <placeName>Jamaica</placeName>&#44; for I value it as the gift of a good<lb/> friend.  By forwarding your letters to <persName>Mrs. HS. Henry</persName> <placeName>16 Broadway New York</placeName><lb/> they will always reach me.  Remember us affectionately to <persName>Miss Gratz</persName>&#44;<lb/> &#38; <persName>Ms.Hart</persName> &#38; <persName>Miss Louisa</persName>&#44; the <persName>Florance</persName> family&#44; <persName>Mr. Abraham N<add>&#63;</add></persName> &#38; family&#44; and all<lb/> old friends&#44; and believe me</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)">Your&#39;s as of old</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)"><persName role="author">M. N. Nathan</persName></p>
